# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-peninsula
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] The number of abortion clinics in Alaska has been declining, going from fourteen in 1982 to thirteen in 1992 to three in 2014.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] 1,547 abortions took place in Alaska in 2014, and 1,459 took place in 2015.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] There is state funding for abortions based on income.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska, California, and New Hampshire did not voluntarily provide the Center for Disease Control with abortion related data in 2000 or 2001.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2014, a poll by the Pew Research Center reported that 63% of adults in the state of Alaska believe abortion should be legal in all or most cases, with 34% stating it should be illegal in all or most cases.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska, Hawaii, Washington, and New York were the only four states that made abortion legal between 1967 and 1970 that did not require a reason to request an abortion.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 1970, the state repealed some of its abortion laws, along with Hawaii, New York, and Washington.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] The following year, Alaska repealed its statute that said inducing an abortion was a criminal offense.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] State law still required in 1971 that any woman getting a legal abortion in the state needed to be a resident for some specific period between 30 and 90 days.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Some states, such as Alaska, Mississippi, West Virginia, Texas, and Kansas, have passed laws requiring abortion providers to warn patients of a link between abortion and breast cancer, and to issue other scientifically unsupported warnings.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] The state was one of 23 states in 2007 to have a detailed abortion-specific informed consent requirement.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Alaska and Minnesota both require that women seeking abortions after 20 weeks be informed that, while experts disagree on the issue of whether or not a fetus can feel pain at 20 weeks, it is possible.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] House Bill 250 was introduced in 2017 by Rep.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] The bill was called the "Life at Conception Act", and it never made it out of committee in Alaska's House.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2017, Washington State, New Mexico, Illinois, Alaska, Maryland, Massachusetts, Connecticut, and New Jersey allow, by state law qualified non-physicians to prescribe drugs for medical abortions only.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In May 2019, Eastman introduced House Bill 178, which defines abortion as "murder of an unborn child"; the bill was never heard before a committee.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2022, Governor Mike Dunleavy expressed interest in an amendment to the Alaska Constitution clarifying the legality of abortion in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] 2022 happened to be the year that Alaska's regularly scheduled ballot question for calling a state constitutional convention was asked.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Dunleavy and other anti-abortion advocates recommended voting "yes", but the question was resoundingly defeated, with 70% voting "no".
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2023, the bipartisan coalition majority in the Alaska State Senate is consensus-focused and unlikely to address controversial topics like abortion.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] The US Supreme Court's decision in 1973's *Roe v.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Wade* ruling meant the state could no longer regulate abortion in the first trimester.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 1997, the Alaska Supreme Court ruled in *Valley Hospital Association, Inc. v.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Mat-Su Coalition for Choice* that the privacy clause of the Alaska Constitution protects the right to an abortion.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] This ruling remains in effect after the US Supreme Court overruled Roe v.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2016, the Alaska Supreme Court struck down a parental notification law that had been established in 2010.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In September 2024, an Alaska superior court judge struck down the requirement that only licensed physicians provide abortions, meaning that the procedure can now also be legally performed by nurse practitioners and physician assistants.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Between 1982 and 1992, the number of abortion clinics in the state decreased by 1, going from 14 in 1982 to 13 in 1992.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2014, there were 3 abortion clinics in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] 90% of the boroughs in the state did not have an abortion clinic.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] That year, 37% of women in the state aged 15–44 lived in a borough without an abortion clinic.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In March 2016, there were 4 Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] There were still 4 Planned Parenthood clinics the following year, all of which offered abortion services, in a state with a population of 167,815 women aged 15–49.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2022, there were three Planned Parenthood clinics in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2024, there were two Planned Parenthood clinics.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 1990, 69,000 women in the state faced the risk of an unintended pregnancy.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2013, among white women aged 15–19, there were 130 abortions, 10 abortions for black women aged 15–19, 20 abortions for Hispanic women aged 15–19, and 70 abortions for women of all other races.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2017, the state had an infant mortality rate of 5.6 deaths per 1,000 live births.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] 17 US states, including Alaska, use their own funds to cover all or most "medically necessary" abortions sought by low-income women under Medicaid, 13 of which are required by State court orders to do so.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] In 2010, the state had 835 publicly funded abortions, all of which were state funded.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Women from the state participated in marches supporting abortion rights as part of a #StoptheBans movement in May 2019.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Hundreds of women attended a rally in Anchorage at Town Square Park to protest legislation proposed in Alaska's House to restrict abortion rights.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] The event was organized by Planned Parenthood Votes and Alaska ACLU.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] There was another rally at the Alaska Capitol in Juneau in May 2019, in opposition to the bill proposed by Republican Rep.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Following the leak of the overturning of Roe v.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] Wade on May 2, 2022, Alaska saw abortion rights protests in Anchorage, Fairbanks, and Haines.
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] David Eastman (R-Wasilla) was censured by the Alaska Legislature in 2017 after he claimed that women used Medicaid support for abortion as a "free trip to the city".
[src:alaska-peninsula/abortion-in-alaska] A small counter-protest was organized by anti-abortion rights activists at the Alaska Capitol in Juneau in May 2019, in support of proposed restrictions on women's ability to access legal abortions in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Ahtna, Inc. stewards over 1,500,000 acres (6,100 km2) of lands granted through land claims under ANCSA finalized between 1971 and 1998.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] The Ahtna region is located primarily in the Copper River Census Area of Alaska, with a small spillover into the neighboring Denali Borough in the area of Cantwell.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Ahtna's total entitlement under ANCSA is 1,770,000 acres (7,160 km2).
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] At incorporation, Ahtna enrolled approximately 1,000 Alaska Natives, each of whom received 100 shares of Ahtna stock.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] As an ANCSA corporation, Ahtna has no publicly traded stock and its shares cannot legally be sold.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] The corporation has over 2,000 shareholders, all of whom are Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Ahtna's total entitlement under ANCSA is 1,770,000 acres (7,160 km2), including regional and village entitlements.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Eight villages are contained within the Ahtna region, including Cantwell, Chistochina, Chitina, Gakona, Gulkana, Mentasta, the Native Village of Kluti-Kaah (Copper Center), and Tazlina.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Under the terms of ANCSA, 714,240 acres (2,890 km2) of land surrounding the villages were allocated to the village corporations established for those villages.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Ahtna, Inc. received bonus selections of about 45,000 acres (182 km2) for distribution among the eight villages based upon historic use and subsistence needs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] In 1980, seven of the eight village corporations in the Ahtna region merged with Ahtna.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] These included the village corporations Yedatene Na Corporation (Cantwell), Cheesh-Na, Incorporated (Chistochina), Gakona Corporation (Gakona), Sta-Keh Corporation (Gulkana), Kluti-Kaah Corporation (Kluti-Kaah in Copper Center), Mentasta, Incorporated (Mentasta), and Tazlina, Incorporated (Tazlina).
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Chitina Native Corporation (in Chitina) chose not to merge with Ahtna, and retains rights to the surface estate of its lands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Rights to the subsurface estate of its lands are with Ahtna, Inc., per the requirements of ANCSA.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Ahtna Netiye', LLC, the holding company of Ahtna, Inc. manages the operating subsidiaries, all of which are wholly owned.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] These subsidiary companies are involved in a number of corporate activities, including civil and vertical construction, environmental remediation, facilities management and support services, government contracting, and oil and gas pipeline maintenance and construction.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Ahtna Netiye', LLC is headquartered in Anchorage, Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/ahtna-incorporated] Under federal law, Ahtna and its majority-owned subsidiaries, joint ventures and partnerships are deemed to be a "minority and economically disadvantaged business enterprise[s]" (43 USC 1626(e)).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The **Alaska Native Regional Corporations** (**ANRC**s) are regional corporations in the United States that administer and settle land and financial claims made by the Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The corporations were established in 1971 when the United States Congress passed the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA), which provided for the establishment of 13 regional corporations to administer such claims.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Under ANCSA the state was originally divided into twelve regions, each represented by a "Native association" responsible for the enrollment of past and present residents of the region.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Individual Alaska Natives enrolled in these associations, and their village level equivalents, were made shareholder in the Regional and Village Corporations created by the Act.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The twelve for-profit regional corporations, and a thirteenth region representing those Alaska Natives who were no longer residents of Alaska in 1971, were awarded the monetary and property compensation created by ANCSA.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Village corporations and their shareholders received compensation through the regional corporations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The fact that many ostensibly Alaska Native villages throughout the state were not empowered by the ANCSA to form village corporations later led to a number of lawsuits.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The regional and village corporations are now owned by Alaska Native people through privately owned shares of corporation stock.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Alaska Natives alive at ANCSA's enactment on December 17, 1971, who enrolled in a Native association (at the regional and/or village level) received 100 shares of stock in the respective corporation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] During the 1970s, ANCSA regional and village corporations selected land in and around native villages in the state in proportion to their enrolled populations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Village corporations own the surface rights to the lands they selected, but regional corporations own the subsurface rights of both their own selections and of those of the village corporations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The Act lays out the specifics of the corporations' status.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] (a) Division of Alaska into twelve geographic regions; common heritage and common interest of region; area of region commensurate with operations of Native association; boundary disputes, arbitration.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] For purposes of this chapter, the State of Alaska shall be divided by the Secretary within one year after December 18, 1971, into twelve geographic regions, with each region composed as far as practicable of Natives having a common heritage and sharing common interests.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] (d) Incorporation; business for profit; eligibility for benefits; provisions in articles for carrying out chapter.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The articles of incorporation shall include provisions necessary to carry out the terms of this chapter.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] There are over 200 village corporations, corresponding to the list of villages published in the text of ANCSA.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Most corporations serve a single village, although some smaller villages have consolidated their corporations over the years.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The Afognak Native Corporation was organized in 1977 through the merger of two ANCSA village corporations: Port Lions Native Corporation and Natives of Afognak, Inc.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] It is governed by a nine-member board of directors.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Afognak Native Corporation has many business interests.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] For 18 years it participated in and profited from timber development ventures on Afogank Island.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] It operates a number of successful subsidiaries including leasing, bioenergy operations and oil field services.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] In the late 1990s, the Afognak Native Corporation launched a government contracting business.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The Afognak Native Corporation is a wealthy corporation and was listed in the Top 100 Contractors of the Federal Government in 2010.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Afognak Native Corporation entities also received NASA Small Business Contractor of the Year Award in 2013.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The Corporation's profile is listed as "Construction and Engineering" services.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The Afognak Native Corporation has approximately 900 shareholders and pays over $12 million in dividends annually.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The Afognak Native Corporation controls over 160,000 acres of land in the Kodiak Archipelago and the lands form the core of financial success of the corporation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] The federal Indian Self-Determination and Education Assistance Act of 1975 (ISDA) gave self-autonomy to both Native Indian tribal governments and to ANCs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] In the wake of the COVID-19 pandemic, the CARES Act set aside about $8 billion in funds for federally-recognized "tribal governments".
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Treasury Department earmarked about $500 million of those funds for ANCs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] That led to the United States Supreme Court case, *Yellen v.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-native-corporation] Confederated Tribes of the Chehalis Reservation*, which was decided in June 2021 that under ISDA, the ANCs were federally-recognized "tribal governments" and thus qualified for CARES funds.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The migration of Alaska Natives' ancestors into the Alaskan region occurred thousands of years ago in multiple waves.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Some present-day groups descend from a later migration event whose descendants gradually settled across northern North America.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native's ancestors are the ones who did not migrate further south or east.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Genetic evidence indicates that these groups are not closely related to the Indigenous peoples of South America.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Evidence from archaeology indicates that the ancestors of Alaska Natives migrated from Asia.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Anthropologists have proposed that their journey to Alaska from Asia was made possible through the Bering land bridge or by traveling across the sea.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Across the Arctic and the circumpolar north, the ancestors of Alaska Natives established a variety of Indigenous cultures that developed and changed over time.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] These cultures demonstrated considerable ingenuity in adapting to harsh climates and environments.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Historically, the defining characteristic of Alaska Native groups has often been their languages, which belong to several major language families.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Currently, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans constitute more than 20% of Alaska's population.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The vast majority of Alaska Natives are either Eskaleut or Na Dene.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] As of 2018, Alaska Natives constituted 15.4% of the overall Alaskan population.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Earlier data from the Alaskan Natives Commission estimated approximately 86,000 Alaska Natives residing in Alaska in 1990, with an additional 17,000 living outside of the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] More recently, a 2013 study conducted by the Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development documented over 120,000 Alaska Native Individuals within Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] While a significant portion of the Alaska Native populations resides in smaller villages or remote regional hubs such as Nome, Dillingham, and Bethel, there has been a notable increase in the percentage living in urban areas.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] According to the 2010 census, 44% of Alaska Natives lived in urban areas, a rise from 38% recorded in the 2000 census.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The pre-contact population of Alaska Natives, in year 1750, before first European settlement, is estimated as around 93,800 people.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In 1870 the native population of Alaska was still estimated as 70,000 people.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] However, the census of 1880 found only 32,996 Native Alaskans.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The population of Alaska Natives then further declined to 25,450 people in 1910 (of whom 25,328 lived in Alaska and 122 in the rest of the United States).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Since 1910 the population began rebounding, and it reached 168,826 people in year 2010.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Of them 124,758 lived in Alaska and 44,068 in the rest of the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The modern history of Alaska Natives began in the eighteenth century with the initial contact between Alaskan First Nations and Russian explorers sailing from Siberia.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Subsequently, in the nineteenth century, British and American traders, coming mostly from eastern settlements in North America, arrived in the region.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In some areas of Alaska, the active presence of Christian missionaries did not occur until the twentieth century.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Vitus Bering spotted Alaska during an expedition.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Subsequently, in the 18th century, Alaska Natives encountered Russians, with the timing of this contact varying among different Native groups across Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Arriving by ship from Siberia, in the mid-eighteenth century, Russians established trade with Alaska Natives, particularly in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] They founded settlements around their trading posts, which included Russian Orthodox missionaries.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] These missionaries were the first to translate Christian scripture into Native languages, such as Tlingit.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The lasting impact of this period is evident in the 21st century with numerous Russian Orthodox Christian congregations in Alaska composed predominantly of Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Sibero-Russian *promyshlenniki*, rather than engaging in hunting and harvesting marine life themselves, coerced the Aleuts into performing this labor, enserfing the Aleuts.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] As news for the fur trade spread, competition among Russian companies intensified.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Catherine the Great, upon ascending to the throne in 1763, expressed goodwill towards the Aleuts and encouraged fair treatment.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] However, the increasing competition between trading companies, which eventually consolidated into larger and more powerful corporations, led to conflicts that worsened relations with the Indigenous populations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Over time, the situation became dire for the Aleuts and other Native Alaskan people affected by Russian contact.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] As the animal populations declined, the Aleuts, already dependent on the new barter economy driven by the fur trade with the Russians, faced increasing pressure to take greater risks in the dangerous waters of the North Pacific to hunt for more otter.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Shelikhov-Golikov Company, and later Russian-American Company developed as a monopoly, using skirmishes and systematic violence as tools for the colonial exploitation of the Indigenous peoples.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] When the Aleut revolted and won some victories, the Russians retaliated with deadly force, destroying their boats and hunting equipment, leaving them no means of survival.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The most devastating impact on the Aleut population during the initial two generations of Russian contact (1741/1759-1781/1799 AD) was the introduction of new diseases from Eurasia.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Approximately 80% of the Aleut population perished from these infectious diseases, to which they had no immunity, unlike Europeans among whom these diseases have been endemic for centuries.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Russian Tsarist government expanded into Indigenous territory in present-day Alaska for its own geopolitical reasons.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] It consumed natural resources of the territory during the trading years, and Russian Orthodoxy was evangelized.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Their movement into these populated areas of Indigenous communities altered the demographic and natural landscape.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Historians have suggested that the Russian-American Company exploited Indigenous peoples as a source of inexpensive labor.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Russian-American Company not only used Indigenous populations for labor during the fur trade, but also held some as hostages to acquire *iasak*.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Iasak, a form of taxation imposed by the Russians, was a tribute in the form of otter pelts.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] It was a taxation method the Russians had previously found useful in their early encounter with Indigenous communities of Siberia during the Siberian fur trade.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Beaver pelts were also customary to be given to fur traders upon first contact with various communities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Russian-American Company used military force on Indigenous families, taking them hostage until male community members produced furs for them.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Otter furs on Kodiak Island and Aleutian Islands enticed the Russians to start these taxations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Robbery and maltreatment in the form of corporal punishment and the withholding of food was also present upon the arrival of fur traders.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Catherine the Great dissolved the giving of tribute in 1799, but her government initiated mandatory conscription of Indigenous men between the ages of 18 and 50 to become seal hunters strictly for the Russian American Company.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] This mandatory labor gave the Russian American Company an edge in competition with American and British fur traders.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] But the conscription separated men from their families and villages, thus altering and breaking down communities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] With able-bodied men away on the hunt, villages were left with little protection as only women, children, and the elderly remained behind.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In addition to changes that came with conscription, the spread of disease also altered the populations of Indigenous communities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Although records kept in the period were scarce, it has been said that 80% of the pre-contact population of the Aleut people were gone by 1800.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native population was first recorded in the 1880 United States census, and it was estimated that the population had declined from 80,000 in 1741 to 33,000 due to disease.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The population continued to decline until 1910 and it was not until 1947 that this number surpassed the 1880 figure.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Relationships between Indigenous women and fur traders increased as Indigenous men were away from villages.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] This resulted in marriages and children that would come to be known as Creole peoples, children who were Indigenous and Russian.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] To reduce hostilities with Aleutian communities, it became policy for fur traders to enter into marriage with Indigenous women.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Creole population increased in the territory controlled by the Russian American Company.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The growth of the Russian Orthodox Church was another important tactic in the colonization and conversion of Indigenous populations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Ioann Veniaminov, who later became Saint Innocent of Alaska, was an important missionary who carried out the Orthodox Church's agenda to Christianize Indigenous populations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The church encouraged Creole children to follow Russian Orthodox Christianity, while the Russian American Company provided them with an education.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Many Orthodox missionaries, like Herman of Alaska, defended Natives from exploitation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Creole people were believed to have high levels of loyalty toward the Russian crown and Russian American Company.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] After completing their education, children were often sent to Russia, where they would study skills such as mapmaking, theology, and military intelligence.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In the 1850s Russia lost much of its interest in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Alaska's abundance of natural resources, particularly gold, drew the interest of the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In 1867, the United States bought Alaska from Russia.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] This purchase happened without considering the opinions of the Native Alaskans, who were not regarded as citizens at the time.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The land traditionally belonging to Alaska Natives was treated as "open land," allowing white settlers to claim it without providing any compensation or recognition to the Native people living there.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The only educational opportunities available for Alaska Natives were in schools established by religious missionaries.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Many white settlers failed to appreciate the complex and well-developed cultures that Alaska Natives had created to thrive in their challenging environment.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Instead, they viewed them as inferior to European Americans, which aligned with white supremacist ideologies.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Klondike Gold Rush of 1896–1898 led to increased white settlement in Alaska and brought discriminatory practices against Indigenous peoples.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] American settlers imposed racial segregation and discriminatory laws similar to Jim Crow laws, which severely limited Alaska Natives' opportunities and cultural practices, effectively treating them as second-class citizens.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] This segregation manifested in various ways, including "whites only" signs that prevented natives from entering certain buildings.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Educational discrimination was also prevalent.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In an 1880 court case, a child was barred from attending school with Americans because his stepfather was native.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Children of mixed heritage could only attend American schools if their families abandoned their native culture.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Simultaneously, the U.S. government implemented policies to disrupt Alaska Native family structures.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Federal records show that disrupting native family units was a deliberate part of Federal Indian policy aimed at assimilating Indigenous children.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Federal Indian Boarding School Initiative played a major role in creating intergenerational trauma by removing children from their native villages and placing them in off-reservation boarding schools alongside children from other tribes.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] This system created artificial communities of Indigenous children throughout the boarding school network, resulting in new Indigenous family structures depending on whether children returned to their native villages or settled elsewhere after completing their education.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] These policies prohibited Alaska Native children from speaking their native languages, wearing traditional clothing, associating with other natives, consuming traditional foods, or practicing their religions.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The resulting family separation and cultural eradication caused significant intergenerational trauma.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In 1912, the Alaska Native Brotherhood (ANB) was formed to help fight for citizenship rights.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native Sisterhood (ANS) was created in 1915.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Also in 1915, the Alaska Territorial legislature passed a law allowing Alaskan Natives the right to vote – but on the condition that they give up their cultural customs and traditions.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Indian Citizenship Act, passed in 1924, gave all Native Americans United States citizenship.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] ANB began to hold a great deal of political power in the 1920s.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] They protested the segregation of Alaska Natives in public areas and institutions, and also staged boycotts.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Alberta Schenck (Inupiaq) staged a well-publicized protest against segregation in a movie theater in 1944.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] With the help of Elizabeth Peratrovich (Tlingit), the Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945 was passed, ending segregation in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In 1942, during World War II, the United States forced evacuation of around nine hundred Aleuts from the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The idea was to remove the Aleuts from a potential combat zone during World War II for their own protection, but European Americans living in the same area were not forced to leave.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The removal was handled so poorly that many Aleuts died after they were evacuated; the elderly and children had the highest mortality rates.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Survivors returned to the islands to find their homes and possessions destroyed or looted.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Civil rights activists such as Alberta Schenck Adams and Elizabeth Peratrovich protested discriminatory laws against Native Alaskans with what were effectively sit-ins and lobbying.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945, the first anti-discrimination state law in the U.S., occurred as a result of these protests.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] It entitled all Alaskans to "full and equal enjoyment" of public areas and businesses, a ban on segregating signs, with discriminatory actions punishable by a $250 fine and up to 30 days in jail.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Alaska became part of the United States in 1959 upon President Dwight D.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Eisenhower recognizing Alaska as the 49th state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In 1971, with the support of Alaska Native leaders such as Emil Notti, Willie Hensley, and Byron Mallott, the U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Congress passed the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA), which settled land and financial claims for lands and resources which the Alaska Natives had lost to European-Americans.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] It provided for the establishment of thirteen Alaska Native Regional Corporations to administer those claims.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Similar to the separately defined status of the Canadian Inuit and First Nations in Canada, which are recognized as distinct peoples, in the United States, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans are in some respects treated separately by the government from other Native Americans in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] This is in part related to their interactions with the U.S. government which occurred in a different historical period than its interactions during the period of westward expansion during the 19th century.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Europeans and Americans did not have sustained encounters with the Alaska Natives until the late 19th and early 20th centuries when many were attracted to the region in gold rushes.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Alaska Natives were not allotted individual title in severalty to land under the Dawes Act of 1887 but were instead treated under the Alaska Native Allotment Act of 1906.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Allotment Act was repealed in 1971, following ANSCA, at which time reservations were ended.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Another characteristic difference is that Alaska Native tribal governments do not have the power to collect taxes for business transacted on tribal land, per the United States Supreme Court decision in *Alaska v.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Native Village of Venetie Tribal Government* (1998).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Except for the Tsimshian, Alaska Natives no longer hold reservations but do control some lands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Under the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972, Alaska Natives reserve the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Four Indigenous tribes in Alaska, the Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes, are among America's first climate refugees due to the impacts of sea ice melting and increased wildfires in their regions.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Climate change has created extensive challenges for Alaska's native peoples, including increased vulnerability to disease, mental health issues, physical injuries, and food and water insecurity.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] According to the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), coastal erosion from sea ice loss is displacing native communities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] This melting also disrupts the migration patterns of animals that tribes depend on for sustenance, while eliminating traditional places to store harvested food.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] As permafrost thaws, existing infrastructure becomes unstable, leading to the collapse of Native villages.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes are situated on Alaska's west coast, where rising sea levels have intensified storm surges that erode their coastlines.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] These communities face forced migration because there is no suitable nearby land to relocate to, requiring them to abandon their traditional ways of life.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Predictions indicate that a significant climate event could completely submerge these tribal lands in fewer than fifteen years.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The changing climate has heightened safety risks for Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] While thick ice layers were historically present year-round, warming temperatures have thinned the ice, increasing incidents of people falling through—a dangerous situation that leads to additional health concerns even for survivors.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Water insecurity and deteriorating infrastructure have created sanitation problems, contributing to an increase in respiratory illnesses across Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In 2005, pneumonia became the leading cause of hospitalizations in these regions.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Many affected communities experience significant psychological stress due to both the immediate impacts of climate change and the complex challenges of relocation without established policies or pathways.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Additional stress comes from infrastructure damage caused by thawing permafrost, with minimal regulatory guidance beyond the Alaskan government's recommendations to avoid building on permafrost or to use extra insulation on foundation walls.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Food security has also deteriorated as animals relocate to more suitable habitats.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Traditional underground ice cellars, once frozen year-round, now thaw during summer months, rendering food supplies inedible.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] Gathering of subsistence food continues to be an important economic and cultural activity for many Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] In Utqiaġvik, Alaska, in 2005, more than 91 percent of the Iñupiat households which were interviewed still participated in the local subsistence economy, compared with the approximately 33 percent of non-Iñupiat households who used wild resources obtained from hunting, fishing, or gathering.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] But, unlike many tribes in the contiguous United States, Alaska Natives do not have treaties with the United States that protect their subsistence rights, except for the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act explicitly extinguished aboriginal hunting and fishing rights in the state of Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] With the exception of the highway connecting Fairbanks to Prudhoe Bay, the region is disconnected from the rest of the Alaskan road system and relies mostly on waterways and small airports for transportation due to the Brooks Range secluding the region from the rest of the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] The entire Arctic coastal plain of Alaska with its Arctic coastal tundra has tremendous ecological importance with the densest concentration of birds in the Arctic, along with housing substantial amounts of large mammals such as whales, walrus, seals, caribou, and moose.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] The region includes the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge (ANWR) as well as the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska (NPRA).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Within the North Slope, only a surface "active layer" of the tundra thaws each season; most of the soil is permanently frozen year-round.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] On top of this permafrost, water flows out to sea via shallow, braided streams or settles into pools and ponds.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Along the bottom of the Landsat 7 image on the right, the rugged terrain of the Brooks Range mountains is snow-covered in places (blue areas) and exposed (pink areas) in others.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Much of the region is located politically in North Slope Borough, and geographically in the Alaska North Slope basin.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] On August 12, 2018, a 6.4 magnitude earthquake hit the region, the most powerful recorded for the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] The region includes the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] The entire coastal plain of Alaska has tremendous ecological importance, with the densest concentration of birds in the Arctic.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Under the North Slope is an ancient seabed, which now contains large amounts of petroleum.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Within the North Slope, there is a geological feature called the Barrow Arch — a belt of the kind of rock known to be able to serve as a trap for oil.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] It runs from the city of Utqiaġvik to a point just west of the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Ira Harkey quotes Noel Wien as stating that in the 1920s, "To keep warm and to cook with, the Eskimo was burning hunks of dark stuff he just picked up on the ground all around his tent.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] This was oil from seepage under the tundra.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] The North Slope region includes the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska (NPRA), which was established by President Warren G.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Harding in 1923 as an oil supply for the US Navy, though the presence of oil in the region had been known by American whalers for some time.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] It constituted the bulk of Alaska's known petroleum until the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field was discovered (outside the NPRA) in 1968, followed by the Kuparuk River oil field in 1969.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] The petroleum extracted from the region is transferred south by means of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System to Valdez on the Pacific Ocean.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] In 2005 the USGS estimated that the Arctic Alaska Petroleum Province, encompassing all the lands and adjacent Continental Shelf areas north of the Brooks Range-Herald arch (see map) held more than 50 billion bbl of oil and natural-gas liquids and 227 trillion cubic feet of gas.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] The source rock for the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field and neighboring reserves is also a potential source for unconventional tight oil and shale gas – possibly containing "up to 2 billion barrels of technically recoverable oil and up to 80 trillion cubic feet of natural gas, according to a 2012 U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Alaska North Slope (ANS) is a more expensive waterborne crude oil.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Since 1987, Alaska North Slope (ANS) crude production has been in decline.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-north-slope] Geological Survey estimated 3.6 billion barrels of oil and 8.9 trillion cubic feet of natural gas in Mississippian through Paleogene strata in the central North Slope of Alaska, which are undiscovered and technically recoverable.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is the largest U.S. state by area—comprising more total area than the next three largest states of Texas, California, and Montana combined—and is the world's largest semi-exclave and seventh-largest subnational division.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] With a population of 740,133 in 2024, it is the third-least populous and most sparsely populated state in the U.S., but the most populous territory in North America located mostly north of the 60th parallel, with more than quadruple the combined populations of Northern Canada and Greenland.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska contains the four largest cities in the United States by area, including the state capital, Juneau.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, and approximately half the state's residents live within its metropolitan area.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Indigenous people have lived in Alaska for thousands of years, and it is widely believed that the region served as the entry point for the initial settlement of the Americas by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Russian Empire was the first to actively colonize the area beginning in the 18th century, eventually establishing Russian America, which spanned most of the current state and promoted and maintained a native Alaskan Creole population.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The expense and logistical difficulty of maintaining this distant possession prompted its sale to the U.S. in 1867 for US$7.2 million, equivalent to $166 million in 2025.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The area went through several administrative changes before becoming organized as a territory on May 11, 1912.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It was admitted as the 49th state of the U.S. on January 3, 1959.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] An abundance of natural resources—including commercial fishing and the extraction of natural gas and oil—has enabled Alaska to have one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States, despite having one of the smallest economies.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Armed Forces bases and tourism also contribute to the economy; more than half of Alaska is federally owned, containing national forests, national parks, and wildlife refuges.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It is among the most irreligious states and one of the first to legalize recreational marijuana.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska has the highest proportion of Native Americans of any U.S. state, at 22 percent.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The name *Alaska* (Russian: Аля́ска, romanized: *Aljáska*) was introduced during the Russian colonial period when it was used to refer to the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It was derived from an Aleut-language idiom, *alaxsxaq*, meaning 'the mainland' or, more literally, 'the object towards which the action of the sea is directed'.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Numerous Indigenous peoples occupied Alaska for thousands of years before the arrival of European peoples to the area.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Linguistic and DNA studies done here have provided evidence for the settlement of North America by way of the Bering land bridge.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] At the Upward Sun River site in the Tanana Valley in Alaska, remains of a six-week-old infant were found.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The baby's DNA showed that she belonged to a population that was genetically separate from other Native groups present elsewhere in the New World at the end of the Pleistocene.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Ben Potter, the University of Alaska Fairbanks archaeologist who unearthed the remains at the Upward Sun River site in 2013, named this new group Ancient Beringian.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Tlingit people developed a society with a matrilineal kinship system of property inheritance and descent in what is present Southeast Alaska, along with parts of British Columbia and the Yukon.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Also in the Southeast were the Haida, now well known for their unique arts.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Tsimshian people came to Alaska from British Columbia in 1887, when President Grover Cleveland, and later the U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Congress, granted them permission to settle on Annette Island and found the town of Metlakatla, Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] All three of these peoples, as well as other Indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast, experienced smallpox outbreaks from the late 18th through the mid-19th century, with the most devastating epidemics occurring in the 1830s and 1860s, resulting in high fatalities and social disruption.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Some researchers believe the first Russian settlement in Alaska was established in the 17th century.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] According to this hypothesis, in 1648 several koches of Semyon Dezhnyov's expedition came ashore in Alaska by storm and founded this settlement.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] This hypothesis is based on the testimony of Chukchi geographer Nikolai Daurkin, who had visited Alaska in 1764–1765 and who had reported on a village on the Kheuveren River, populated by "bearded men" who "pray to the icons".
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Some modern researchers associate the Kheuveren with the Koyuk River.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The first European vessel to reach Alaska is generally held to be the *St.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Gabriel* under the authority of the surveyor M.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Fyodorov on August 21, 1732, during an expedition of Siberian Cossack A.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Shestakov and Russian explorer Dmitry Pavlutsky (1729–1735).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Another European contact with Alaska occurred in 1741, when Vitus Bering led an expedition for the Russian Navy aboard the *St.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] After his crew returned to Russia with sea otter pelts judged to be the finest fur in the world, small associations of fur traders began to sail from the shores of Siberia toward the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The first permanent European settlement was founded in 1784.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] From 1774 to 1800, Spain sent several expeditions to Alaska to assert its claim over the Pacific Northwest, which it considered part of New Spain, administered from Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 1789, a Spanish settlement and fort were built in Nootka Sound.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] These expeditions gave names to places such as Valdez, Bucareli Sound, and Cordova.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Later, the Russian-American Company carried out an expanded colonization program during the early-to-mid-19th century.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Sitka, renamed New Archangel from 1804 to 1867, on Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in what is now Southeast Alaska, became the capital of Russian America.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It remained the capital after the colony was transferred to the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Russians never fully colonized Alaska, and the colony was never very profitable.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Evidence of Russian settlement in names and churches survives throughout southeastern Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Seward, the United States Secretary of State under President Andrew Johnson, negotiated the Alaska Purchase, referred to pejoratively as Seward's Folly, with the Russians for $7.2 million.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Russian emperor Alexander II also planned the sale.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The purchase was made on March 30, 1867.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Six months later the commissioners arrived in Sitka and the formal transfer was arranged.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The flag-raising took place at Fort Sitka on October 18, 1867.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In the ceremony, 250 uniformed U.S. soldiers marched to the governor's house at "Castle Hill", where the Russian troops lowered the Russian flag and the U.S. flag was raised.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] This event is celebrated as Alaska Day, a legal holiday on October 18.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska was loosely governed by the military initially and was administered as a district starting in 1884, with a governor appointed by the United States president.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] A federal district court was headquartered in Sitka.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] For most of Alaska's first decade under the United States flag, Sitka was the only community inhabited by American settlers.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] They organized "a provisional city government", which was Alaska's first municipal government, but not in a legal sense.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Legislation allowing Alaskan communities to legally incorporate as cities arrived in 1900, and home rule for cities was extremely limited or unavailable until statehood took effect in 1959.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Starting in the 1890s and stretching in some places to the early 1910s, gold rushes in Alaska and the nearby Yukon Territory brought thousands of miners and settlers to Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 1912, Alaska was incorporated as an organized territory.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska's capital, which had been in Sitka until 1906, was moved north to Juneau.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Construction of the Alaska Governor's Mansion began that same year.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] European immigrants from Norway and Sweden also settled in southeast Alaska, where they entered the fishing and logging industries.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] During World War II, the Aleutian Islands Campaign focused on Attu, Agattu and Kiska, all of which were occupied by the Empire of Japan.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] During the Japanese occupation, an American civilian and two United States Navy personnel were killed at Attu and Kiska respectively, and almost 50 Aleut civilians and eight sailors were interned in Japan.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] About half of the Aleuts died during the period of internment.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Unalaska/Dutch Harbor and Adak became significant bases for the United States Army, United States Army Air Forces and United States Navy.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The United States Lend-Lease program involved flying American warplanes through Canada to Fairbanks and then Nome.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Soviet pilots took possession of these aircraft, ferrying them to fight the German invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The construction of military bases contributed to the population growth of some Alaskan cities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Statehood for Alaska was an important cause of James Wickersham early in his tenure as a congressional delegate.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Decades later, the statehood movement gained its first real momentum following a territorial referendum in 1946.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Alaska Statehood Committee and Alaska's Constitutional Convention soon followed.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Statehood supporters also found themselves fighting major battles against political foes, mostly in the U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska was officially proclaimed a state on January 3, 1959.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] On March 27, 1964, the Good Friday earthquake killed 133 people and destroyed several villages and portions of large coastal communities, mainly by the resultant tsunamis and landslides.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It was the fourth-most-powerful earthquake in recorded history, with a moment magnitude of 9.2, more than a thousand times as powerful as the 1989 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The time of day (5:36 pm), time of year (spring) and location of the epicenter were all cited as factors in potentially sparing thousands of lives, particularly in Anchorage.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Good Friday earthquake lasted 4 minutes and 38 seconds.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Six hundred miles (970 km) of fault ruptured at once and moved up to 60 ft (18 m), releasing about 500 years of stress buildup.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Soil liquefaction, fissures, landslides, and other ground failures caused major structural damage in several communities and much damage to property.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Anchorage sustained great destruction or damage to many inadequately earthquake-engineered houses, buildings, and infrastructure (paved streets, sidewalks, water and sewer mains, electrical systems, and other human-made equipment), particularly in the several landslide zones along Knik Arm.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Two hundred miles (320 km) southwest, some areas near Kodiak were permanently raised by 30 feet (9 m).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Southeast of Anchorage, areas around the head of Turnagain Arm near Girdwood and Portage dropped as much as 8 feet (2.4 m), requiring reconstruction and fill to raise the Seward Highway above the new high tide mark.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In Prince William Sound, Port Valdez suffered a massive underwater landslide, resulting in the deaths of 32 people between the collapse of the Valdez city harbor and docks, and inside the ship that was docked there at the time.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Nearby, a 27-foot (8.2 m) tsunami destroyed the village of Chenega, killing 23 of the 68 people who lived there; survivors out-ran the wave, climbing to high ground.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Post-quake tsunamis severely affected Whittier, Seward, Kodiak, and other Alaskan communities, as well as people and property in British Columbia, Washington, Oregon, and California.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Tsunamis also caused damage in Hawaii and Japan.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Evidence of motion directly related to the earthquake was also reported from Florida and Texas.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska had never experienced a major disaster in a highly populated area before and had very limited resources for dealing with the effects of such an event.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In Anchorage, at the urging of geologist Lidia Selkregg, the City of Anchorage and the Alaska State Housing Authority appointed a team of 40 scientists, including geologists, soil scientists, and engineers, to assess the damage done by the earthquake to the city.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The team, called the Engineering and Geological Evaluation Group, was headed by Ruth A.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Schmidt, a geology professor at the University of Alaska Anchorage.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The team of scientists came into conflict with local developers and downtown business owners who wanted to immediately rebuild; the scientists wanted to identify future dangers to ensure that the rebuilt infrastructure would be safe.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The team produced a report on May 8, 1964, just a little more than a month after the earthquake.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The United States military, which has a large active presence in Alaska, also stepped in to assist within moments of the end of the quake.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Army rapidly re-established communications with the lower 48 states, deployed troops to assist the citizens of Anchorage, and dispatched a convoy to Valdez.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] On the advice of military and civilian leaders, President Lyndon B.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Johnson declared all of Alaska a major disaster area the day after the quake.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Coast Guard deployed ships to isolated coastal communities to assist with immediate needs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Bad weather and poor visibility hampered air rescue and observation efforts the day after the quake, but on Sunday the 29th the situation improved and rescue helicopters and observation aircraft were deployed.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] A military airlift immediately began shipping relief supplies to Alaska, eventually delivering 2,570,000 pounds (1,170,000 kg) of food and other supplies.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Broadcast journalist, Genie Chance, assisted in recovery and relief efforts, staying on the KENI air waves over Anchorage for more than 24 continuous hours as the voice of calm from her temporary post within the Anchorage Public Safety Building.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] She was effectively designated as the public safety officer by the city's police chief.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Army Corps of Engineers led the effort to rebuild roads, clear debris, and establish new townsites for communities that had been completely destroyed, at a cost of $110 million.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The West Coast and Alaska Tsunami Warning Center was formed as a direct response to the disaster.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Federal disaster relief funds paid for reconstruction as well as financially supporting the devastated infrastructure of Alaska's government, spending hundreds of millions of dollars that helped keep Alaska financially solvent until the discovery of massive oil deposits at Prudhoe Bay.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Defense Department, the Alaska National Guard founded the Alaska Division of Emergency Services to respond to any future disasters.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The 1968 discovery of oil at Prudhoe Bay and the 1977 completion of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System led to an oil boom.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Royalty revenues from oil have funded large state budgets from 1980 onward.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Oil production was not the only economic value of Alaska's land.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Alaska discovered tourism as an important source of revenue.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Tourism became popular after World War II when military personnel stationed in the region returned home praising its natural splendor.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Alcan Highway, built during the war, and the Alaska Marine Highway System, completed in 1963, made the state more accessible than before.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Tourism has become increasingly important in Alaska, and today more than 1.4 million people visit the state each year.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] With tourism more vital to the economy, environmentalism rose in importance.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Because of the Act, Alaska now contains two-thirds of all American national parklands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Today, more than half of Alaskan land is owned by the Federal Government.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 1989, the *Exxon Valdez* hit a reef in the Prince William Sound, spilling more than 11 million gallons (42 megalitres) of crude oil over 1,100 miles (1,800 km) of coastline.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Today, the battle between philosophies of development and conservation is seen in the contentious debate over oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge and the proposed Pebble Mine.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Located at the northwest corner of North America very near to Asia, Alaska is the northernmost and westernmost state in the United States, but also has the most easterly longitude in the United States because the Aleutian Islands extend into the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is the only non-contiguous U.S. state on continental North America; about 500 miles (800 km) of Canadian territory consisting of British Columbia (in Canada) separates Alaska from Washington.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It is technically part of the continental U.S., but is not usually included in the colloquial use of the term; Alaska is not part of the contiguous U.S., often called "the Lower 48".
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The capital city, Juneau, is situated on the mainland of the North American continent but is not connected by road to the rest of the North American highway system.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The largest lake in Alaska is Lake Illiamna.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is bordered by Canada's Yukon and British Columbia to the east (making it the only state to border only a Canadian territory); the Gulf of Alaska and the Pacific Ocean to the south and southwest; the Bering Sea, Bering Strait, and Chukchi Sea to the west; and the Arctic Ocean to the north.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska's territorial waters touch Russia's territorial waters in the Bering Strait, as the Russian Big Diomede Island and Alaskan Little Diomede Island are only 3 miles (4.8 km) apart.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska has a longer coastline than all the other U.S. states combined.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] At 663,268 square miles (1,717,856 km2) in total area, Alaska is by far the largest state in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is more than twice the size of the second-largest U.S. state (Texas), and it is larger than the next three largest states (Texas, California, and Montana) combined.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is the seventh largest subnational division in the world.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] If it was an independent nation, it would be the 18th largest country in the world; almost the same size as Iran.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] With its myriad islands, Alaska has nearly 34,000 miles (55,000 km) of tidal shoreline.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Aleutian Islands chain extends west from the southern tip of the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Many active volcanoes are found in the Aleutians and in coastal regions.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Unimak Island, for example, is home to Mount Shishaldin, which is an occasionally smoldering volcano that rises to 10,000 feet (3,000 m) above the North Pacific.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The chain of volcanoes extends to Mount Spurr, west of Anchorage on the mainland.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Geologists have identified Alaska as part of Wrangellia, a large region consisting of multiple states and Canadian provinces in the Pacific Northwest, which is actively undergoing continent building.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] One of the world's largest tides occurs in Turnagain Arm, just south of Anchorage, where tidal differences can be more than 35 feet (10.7 m).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska has more than 409,000 natural lakes at least one hectare or bigger.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Marshlands and wetland permafrost cover 188,320 square miles (487,700 km2) (mostly in northern, western and southwest flatlands).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Glacier ice covers about 28,957 square miles (75,000 km2) of Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Bering Glacier is the largest glacier in North America, covering 2,008 square miles (5,200 km2) alone.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The most populous region of Alaska contains Anchorage, the Matanuska-Susitna Valley and the Kenai Peninsula.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Rural, mostly unpopulated areas south of the Alaska Range and west of the Wrangell Mountains also fall within the definition of South Central, as do the Prince William Sound area and the communities of Cordova and Valdez.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Also referred to as the Panhandle or Inside Passage, this is the region of Alaska closest to the contiguous states.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] As such, this was where most of the initial non-indigenous settlement occurred in the years following the Alaska Purchase.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The region is dominated by the Alexander Archipelago as well as the Tongass National Forest, the largest national forest in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It contains the state capital Juneau, the former capital Sitka, and Ketchikan, at one time Alaska's largest city.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Alaska Marine Highway provides a vital surface transportation link throughout the area and country, as only three communities (Haines, Hyder and Skagway) enjoy direct connections to the contiguous North American road system.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Interior is the largest region of Alaska; much of it is uninhabited wilderness.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Fairbanks is the only large city in the region.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Denali National Park and Preserve is located here.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Denali, federally designated as Mount McKinley, is the highest mountain in North America and is also located here.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The North Slope is mostly tundra peppered with small villages.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The area is known for its massive reserves of crude oil and contains both the National Petroleum Reserve–Alaska and the Prudhoe Bay Oil Field.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The city of Utqiaġvik, formerly known as Barrow, is the northernmost city in the United States and is located here.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Northwest Arctic area, anchored by Kotzebue and also containing the Kobuk River valley, is often considered part of this region.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The respective Inupiat of the North Slope and of the Northwest Arctic seldom consider themselves to be one people.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Southwest Alaska is a sparsely inhabited region stretching some 500 miles (800 km) inland from the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Most of the population lives along the coast.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Kodiak Island is also located in the Southwest.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The massive Yukon–Kuskokwim Delta, one of the largest river deltas in the world, is here.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Portions of the Alaska Peninsula are considered part of the Southwest, with the Aleutian Islands often (but not always) being grouped in as well.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] While primarily part of Southwest Alaska when grouped economically, the Aleutian islands are sometimes recognized as an alternate group from the rest of the region due to the geographic separation from the continent.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] More than 300 small volcanic islands make up this chain, which stretches more than 1,200 miles (1,900 km) into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Some of these islands fall in the Eastern Hemisphere, but the International Date Line was drawn west of 180° to keep the whole state, and thus the entire North American continent, within the same legal day.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Two of the islands, Attu and Kiska, were occupied by Japanese forces during World War II.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] As of 2023 the United States Bureau of Land Management manages 290 million surface and subsurface acres as public lands, including a multitude of national forests, national parks, national wildlife refuges, and federal mineral estate land.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Of these, the Bureau of Land Management manages 87 million acres (35 million hectares), or 23.8% of the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Arctic National Wildlife Refuge is managed by the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It is the world's largest wildlife refuge, comprising 16 million acres (6.5 million hectares).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Of the remaining land area, the state of Alaska owns 101 million acres (41 million hectares), its entitlement under the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] A portion of that acreage is occasionally ceded to the organized boroughs presented above, under the statutory provisions pertaining to newly formed boroughs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Smaller portions are set aside for rural subdivisions and other homesteading-related opportunities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] These are not very popular due to the often remote and roadless locations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The University of Alaska, as a land grant university, also owns substantial acreage which it manages independently.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Another 44 million acres (18 million hectares) are owned by 12 regional, and scores of local, Native corporations created under the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA) of 1971.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Regional Native corporation Doyon, Limited often promotes itself as the largest private landowner in Alaska in advertisements and other communications.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Provisions of ANCSA allowing the corporations' land holdings to be sold on the open market starting in 1991 were repealed before they could take effect.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Effectively, the corporations hold title (including subsurface title in many cases, a privilege denied to individual Alaskans) but cannot sell the land.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Individual Native allotments are sold on the open market.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Various private interests own the remaining land, totaling about one percent of the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is, by a large margin, the state with the smallest percentage of private land ownership when Native corporation holdings are excluded.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Alaska Heritage Resources Survey (AHRS) is a restricted inventory of all reported historic and prehistoric sites within the U.S. state of Alaska; it is maintained by the Office of History and Archaeology.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The survey's inventory of cultural resources includes objects, structures, buildings, sites, districts, and travel ways, with a general provision that they are more than fifty years old.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] As of 31 January 2012, more than 35,000 sites have been reported.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Unlike most of U.S. states, Alaska is not divided into counties.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Similarly to Louisiana's parishes, it is divided into *boroughs*.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Delegates to the Alaska Constitutional Convention wanted to avoid the pitfalls of the traditional county system and adopted their own unique model.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Many of the more densely populated parts of the state are part of Alaska's 16 boroughs, which function somewhat similarly to counties in other states.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Unlike county-equivalents in the other states, the boroughs do not cover the state's entire land area.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The area not part of any borough is referred to as the Unorganized Borough.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Unorganized Borough has no government of its own, but the U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Census Bureau in cooperation with the state divided the Unorganized Borough into 11 census areas solely for the purposes of statistical analysis and presentation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] A *recording district* is a mechanism for management of the public record in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The state is divided into 34 recording districts which are centrally administered under a state recorder.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] All recording districts use the same acceptance criteria, fee schedule, etc., for accepting documents into the public record.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Whereas many U.S. states use a three-tiered system of decentralization—state/county/township—most of Alaska uses two tiers—state/borough.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Owing to the low population density, most of the land is located in the Unorganized Borough.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] As the name implies, it has no intermediate borough government but is administered directly by the state government.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2000, 57.71% of Alaska's area has this status, with 13.05% of the population.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 1975, Anchorage merged the city government with the Greater Anchorage Area Borough to form the Municipality of Anchorage, containing the city proper and the communities of Eagle River, Chugiak, Peters Creek, Girdwood, Bird, and Indian.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Fairbanks has a separate borough (the Fairbanks North Star Borough) and municipality (the City of Fairbanks).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska's most populous city is Anchorage, home to 291,247 people in 2020.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The richest location in Alaska by per capita income is Denali ($42,245).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Yakutat, Sitka, Juneau, and Anchorage are the four largest cities in the U.S. by area.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In the 2020 United States census, Alaska has 355 incorporated cities and census-designated places (CDPs).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The tally of cities includes four unified municipalities, essentially the equivalent of a consolidated city–county.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The majority of these communities are located in the rural expanse of Alaska known as "The Bush" and are unconnected to that contiguous North American road network.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The table at the bottom of this section lists the 100 largest cities and census-designated places in Alaska, in population order.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Of Alaska's 2020 U.S. census population figure of 733,391, 16,655 people, or 2.27% of the population, did not live in an incorporated city or census-designated place.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Approximately three-quarters of that figure were people who live in urban and suburban neighborhoods on the outskirts of the city limits of Ketchikan, Kodiak, Palmer and Wasilla.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] CDPs have not been established for these areas by the United States Census Bureau.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Seven CDPs were established for the Ketchikan-area neighborhoods in the 1980 census (Clover Pass, Herring Cove, Ketchikan East, Mountain Point, Alaska Route 7, Pennock Island and Saxman East), but have not been used since.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The remaining population was scattered throughout Alaska, both within organized boroughs and in the Unorganized Borough, in largely remote areas.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is the coldest state in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The climate in the south and southeastern Alaska is a mid-latitude oceanic climate (Köppen climate classification: *Cfb*), and a subarctic oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfc*) in the northern parts, with cool summers and relatively mild winters.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] On an annual basis, the southeast is both the wettest and warmest part of Alaska with milder temperatures in the winter and high precipitation throughout the year.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Juneau averages over 50 in (130 cm) of precipitation a year, and Ketchikan averages over 150 in (380 cm).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] This is also the only region in Alaska in which the average daytime high temperature is above freezing during the winter months.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The climate of Anchorage and south central Alaska is mild by Alaskan standards due to the region's proximity to the seacoast.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] While the area gets less rain than southeast Alaska, it gets more snow, and days tend to be clearer.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] On average, Anchorage receives 16 in (41 cm) of precipitation a year, with around 75 in (190 cm) of snow, although there are areas in the south central which receive far more snow.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic climate (Köppen: *Dfc*) due to its brief, cool summers.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The climate of western Alaska is determined in large part by the Bering Sea and the Gulf of Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] It is a subarctic oceanic climate in the southwest and a continental subarctic climate farther north.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The temperature is somewhat moderate considering how far north the area is.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] This region has a tremendous amount of variety in precipitation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] An area stretching from the northern side of the Seward Peninsula to the Kobuk River valley (i.e., the region around Kotzebue Sound) is technically a desert, with portions receiving less than 10 in (25 cm) of precipitation annually.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] On the other extreme, some locations between Dillingham and Bethel average around 100 in (250 cm) of precipitation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The climate of the interior of Alaska is subarctic and is a classic example of a continental subarctic climate, except in a few valleys where the climate approaches humid continental (Köppen: *Dfb*).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Some of the highest and lowest temperatures in Alaska occur around the area near Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Summers are warm, albeit generally short, and may have temperatures reaching into the 90s °F (the low-to-mid 30s °C).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In the long and very cold winters, the temperature can fall below −60 °F (−51 °C).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Precipitation is sparse in the Interior, often less than 10 in (25 cm) a year, but what precipitation falls in the winter tends to stay the entire winter.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The highest and lowest recorded temperatures in Alaska are both in the Interior.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The highest is 100 °F (38 °C) in Fort Yukon, which is just 8 mi or 13 km inside the arctic circle, on June 27, 1915, making Alaska tied with Hawaii as the state with the lowest high temperature in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The lowest official Alaska temperature is −80 °F (−62 °C) in Prospect Creek on January 23, 1971, one degree above the lowest temperature recorded in continental North America (in Snag, Yukon, Canada).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The climate in the extreme north of Alaska, north of the Brooks Range, is Arctic (Köppen: *ET*) with long, very cold winters and short, cool summers.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Even in July, the average low temperature in Utqiaġvik is 34 °F (1 °C).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Precipitation is light in this part of Alaska, with many places averaging less than 10 in (25 cm) per year, mostly as snow which stays on the ground almost the entire year.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The United States Census Bureau found in the 2020 United States census that the population of Alaska was 733,391 on April 1, 2020, a 3.3% increase since the 2010 United States census.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In the 2010 United States Census, Alaska had a population of 710,231, an increase of 13.3%, up from 626,932 at the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2020, Alaska ranked as the 48th largest state by population, ahead of only Vermont and Wyoming.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is the least densely populated state, and one of the most sparsely populated areas in the world, at 1.2 inhabitants per square mile (0.46/km2).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The next state, Wyoming, has 5.8 inhabitants per square mile (2.2/km2).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is by far the largest U.S. state by area, and the tenth wealthiest, per capita income.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] As of 2018 due to its population size, it is one of 14 U.S. states that still have only one telephone area code.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 2,320 homeless people in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The 2019 American Community Survey estimated 60.2% of the population was white, 3.7% black or African American, 15.6% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.5% Asian, 1.4% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 7.5% two or more races, and 7.3% Hispanic or Latin American.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] At the survey estimates, 7.8% of the total population was foreign-born from 2015 to 2019.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2015, 61.3% were white, 3.4% black or African American, 13.3% American Indian or Alaska Native, 6.2% Asian, 0.9% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 0.3% some other race, and 7.7% multiracial.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Hispanics and Latin Americans were 7% of the state population in 2015.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] From 2015 to 2019, the largest Hispanic and Latin American groups were Mexican Americans, Puerto Ricans, and Cuban Americans.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The largest Asian groups living in the state were Filipinos, Korean Americans, and Japanese and Chinese Americans.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaska was 64.1% white, 14.8% American Indian and Alaska Native, 5.4% Asian, 3.3% black or African American, 1.0% Native Hawaiian and other Pacific Islander, 1.6% from some other race, and 7.3% from two or more races in 2010.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Hispanics or Latin Americans made up 5.5% of the population in 2010.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] As of 2011, 50.7% of Alaska's population younger than one year of age belonged to minority groups (i.e., did not have two parents of white ancestry).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 1960, the United States Census Bureau reported Alaska's population as 77.2% white, 3% black, and 18.8% American Indian and Alaska Native.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2018, the top countries of origin for Alaska's immigrants were the Philippines, Mexico, Canada, Thailand and South Korea.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In the 2011 American Community Survey, 83.4% of people over the age of five spoke only English at home.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] About 3.5% spoke Spanish at home, 2.2% spoke another Indo-European language, about 4.3% spoke an Asian language (including Tagalog), and about 5.3% spoke other languages at home.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey determined 83.7% spoke only English, and 16.3% spoke another language other than English.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The most spoken European language after English was Spanish, spoken by approximately 4.0% of the state population.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Collectively, Asian and Pacific Islander languages were spoken by 5.6% of Alaskans.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Since 2010, 5.2% of Alaskans speak one of the state's 20 Indigenous languages, known locally as "Native languages".
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska is also known for a distinctive dialect of Russian, named Alaskan Russian.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Alaska Native Language Center at the University of Alaska Fairbanks claims that at least twenty Alaska Native languages exist and there are also some languages with different dialects.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Most of Alaska's Native languages belong to either the Eskimo–Aleut or Na-Dene language families.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Some languages are thought to be isolates (e.g., Haida) or have not yet been classified (e.g., Tsimshianic).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2014, nearly all of Alaska's Native languages were classified as either threatened, shifting, moribund, nearly extinct, or dormant languages.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In October 2014, the governor of Alaska signed a bill declaring the state's 20 Indigenous languages to have official status.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] This bill gave them symbolic recognition as official languages, though they have not been adopted for official use within the government.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In May 2024, a bill replaced Tanana with Middle Tanana and Lower Tanana, added Cupʼig and Wetał.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Multiple surveys have ranked Alaska among the most irreligious states.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] ChangePoint in south Anchorage (left) and Anchorage Baptist Temple in east Anchorage are Alaska's largest churches in terms of attendance and membership.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2010, per the Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), about 34% of Alaska residents were members of religious congregations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Of the religious population, roughly 4% were Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 1% Buddhist, 0.2% Baháʼí, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2010, the largest religious denominations in Alaska were the Catholic Church with 50,866 adherents; non-denominational Evangelicals with 38,070 adherents; The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints with 32,170 adherents; and the Southern Baptist Convention with 19,891 adherents.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska has been identified, along with Washington and Oregon in the Pacific Northwest, as being the least religious states in the United States, in terms of church membership.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Pew Research Center in 2014 determined 62% of the adult population practiced Christianity.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Of the Christian denominations, Catholicism was the largest Christian group.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] When Protestant denominations were combined, Protestantism was the largest Christian tradition, with Evangelicalism being the largest movement within the Protestant group.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The unaffiliated population made up the largest non-Christian religious affiliation at 37%.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Atheists made up 5% of the population and the largest non-Christian religion was Buddhism.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2020, the Public Religion Research Institute (PRRI) determined 57% of adults were Christian.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] By 2022, Christianity increased to 77% of the population according to the PRRI.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Through the Association of Religion Data Archives in 2020, its Christian population was dominated by non/inter-denominational Protestantism as the single largest Christian cohort, with 73,930 adherents.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Roman Catholics were second with 40,280 members; throughout its Christian population, non-denominational Christians had an adherence rate of 100.81 per 1,000 residents, and Catholics 54.92 per 1,000 residents.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Per 2014's Pew study, religion was seen as very important to 41% of the population, although 29% considered it somewhat important.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2014, Pew determined roughly 55% believed in God with absolute certainty, and 24% believed fairly certainly.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Reflecting the separate 2020 ARDA study, the 2014 Pew study showed 30% attended religious services once a week, 34% once or twice a month, and 36% seldom/never.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 1795, the first Russian Orthodox Church was established in Kodiak.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Intermarriage with Alaska Natives helped the Russian immigrants integrate into society.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] As a result, an increasing number of Russian Orthodox churches gradually became established within Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaska also has the largest Quaker population (by percentage) of any state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2009, there were 6,000 Jews in Alaska, for whom observance of halakha may pose special problems.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Alaskan Hindus often share venues and celebrations with members of other Asian religious communities, including Sikhs and Jains.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2010, Alaskan Hindus established the Sri Ganesha Temple of Alaska, making it the first Hindu Temple in Alaska and the northernmost Hindu Temple in the world.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] There are an estimated 2,000–3,000 Hindus in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The vast majority of Hindus live in Anchorage or Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Estimates for the number of Muslims in Alaska range from 2,000 to 5,000.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] In 2020, ARDA estimated there were 400 Muslims in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] The Islamic Community Center of Anchorage began efforts in the late 1990s to construct a mosque in Anchorage.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] They broke ground on a building in south Anchorage in 2010 and were nearing completion in late 2014.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] When completed, the mosque was the first in the state and one of the northernmost mosques in the world.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] There is also a Baháʼí center, and there were 690 adherents in 2020.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p01] Additionally, there were 469 adherents of Hinduism and Yoga altogether in 2020, and a small number of Buddhists were present.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In October 2022, Alaska had a total employment of 316,900.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The number of employer establishments was 21,077.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] As of August 2025, the unemployment rate was 4.7%.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The state's historically lowest unemployment rate was recorded in August 2022 at 3.8%, and its highest in May 2020 at 11.7%.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, Alaska's gross state product was $75.011 billion in 2025.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Its per capita personal income was $80,175 in 2025.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] According to a 2013 study by Phoenix Marketing International, Alaska had the fifth-largest number of millionaires per capita in the United States, with a ratio of 6.75 percent.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The oil and gas industry dominates the Alaskan economy, with more than 80% of the state's revenues derived from petroleum extraction.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's main export product, excluding oil and natural gas, is seafood, primarily salmon, cod, pollock and crab.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Agriculture represents a minuscule fraction of the Alaskan economy.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Agricultural production is primarily for consumption within the state and includes nursery stock, dairy products, vegetables, and livestock.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Manufacturing is limited, with most foodstuffs and general goods imported from elsewhere.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Employment is primarily in government and industries such as natural resource extraction, shipping, and transportation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Military bases are a significant component of the economy in Anchorage and the Fairbanks North Star and Kodiak Island boroughs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2025, 99.1% of Alaska businesses are small businesses and employ 54.2% of the state's workforce.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Federal subsidies are also an important part of the economy, allowing the state to keep taxes low.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Its industrial outputs are crude petroleum, natural gas, coal, gold, precious metals, zinc and other mining, seafood processing, timber and wood products.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] There is also a growing service and tourism sector.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Tourists have contributed to the economy by supporting local lodging.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska has vast energy resources, although its oil reserves have been largely depleted.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Major oil and gas reserves were found in the Alaska North Slope (ANS) and Cook Inlet basins, but according to the Energy Information Administration, by February 2014 Alaska had fallen to fourth place in the nation in crude oil production after Texas, North Dakota, and California.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Prudhoe Bay on Alaska's North Slope is still the second highest-yielding oil field in the United States, typically producing about 400,000 barrels per day (64,000 m3/d), although by early 2014 North Dakota's Bakken Formation was producing over 900,000 barrels per day (140,000 m3/d).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Trans-Alaska Pipeline can transport and pump up to 2.1 million barrels (330,000 m3) of crude oil per day, more than any other crude oil pipeline in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Substantial coal deposits are found in Alaska's bituminous, sub-bituminous, and lignite coal basins.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The United States Geological Survey estimates that there are 85.4 trillion cubic feet (2,420 km3) of undiscovered, technically recoverable gas from natural gas hydrates on the Alaskan North Slope.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska also offers some of the highest hydroelectric power potential in the country from its numerous rivers.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Large swaths of the Alaskan coastline offer wind and geothermal energy potential as well.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's economy depends heavily on increasingly expensive diesel fuel for heating, transportation, electric power and light.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Although wind and hydroelectric power are abundant and underdeveloped, proposals for statewide energy systems were judged uneconomical (at the time of the report, 2001) due to low (less than 50¢/gal) fuel prices, long distances and low population.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Permanent Fund is a constitutionally authorized appropriation of oil revenues, established by voters in 1976 to manage a surplus in state petroleum revenues from oil, largely in anticipation of the then recently constructed Trans-Alaska Pipeline System.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The fund was originally proposed by Governor Keith Miller on the eve of the 1969 Prudhoe Bay lease sale, out of fear that the legislature would spend the entire proceeds of the sale (which amounted to $900 million) at once.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] It was later championed by Governor Jay Hammond and Kenai state representative Hugh Malone.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] It has served as an attractive political prospect ever since, diverting revenues which would normally be deposited into the general fund.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Constitution was written so as to discourage dedicating state funds for a particular purpose.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund has become the rare exception to this, mostly due to the political climate of distrust existing during the time of its creation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] From its initial principal of $734,000, the fund has grown to $50 billion as a result of oil royalties and capital investment programs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Most if not all the principal is invested conservatively outside Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] This has led to frequent calls by Alaskan politicians for the Fund to make investments within Alaska, though such a stance has never gained momentum.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Every year, the state legislature takes out 8% from the earnings, puts 3% back into the principal for inflation proofing, and the remaining 5% is distributed to all qualifying Alaskans.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Permanent Fund is often considered to be one of the leading examples of a basic income policy in the world.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The cost of goods in Alaska has long been higher than in the contiguous 48 states.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Federal government employees, particularly United States Postal Service (USPS) workers and active-duty military members, receive a Cost of Living Allowance usually set at 25% of base pay because, while the cost of living has gone down, it is still one of the highest in the country.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Rural Alaska suffers from severely high prices for food and consumer goods compared to the rest of the country, due to the relatively limited transportation infrastructure.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Due to the northern climate and short growing season, relatively little farming occurs in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Most farms are in either the Matanuska Valley, about 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Anchorage, or on the Kenai Peninsula, about 60 miles (97 km) southwest of Anchorage.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The short 100-day growing season limits the crops that can be grown, but the long sunny summer days make for productive growing seasons.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The primary crops are potatoes, carrots, lettuce, and cabbage.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Tanana Valley is another notable agricultural locus, especially the Delta Junction area, about 100 miles (160 km) southeast of Fairbanks, with a sizable concentration of farms growing agronomic crops; these farms mostly lie north and east of Fort Greely.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] This area was largely set aside and developed under a state program spearheaded by Hammond during his second term as governor.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Delta-area crops consist predominantly of barley and hay.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] West of Fairbanks lies another concentration of small farms catering to restaurants, the hotel and tourist industry, and community-supported agriculture.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaskan agriculture has experienced a surge in growth of market gardeners, small farms and farmers' markets in recent years, with the highest percentage increase (46%) in the nation in growth in farmers' markets in 2011, compared to 17% nationwide.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The peony industry has also taken off, as the growing season allows farmers to harvest during a gap in supply elsewhere in the world, thereby filling a niche in the flower market.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska, with no counties, lacks county fairs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Instead, a small assortment of state and local fairs (with the Alaska State Fair in Palmer the largest), are held mostly in the late summer.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The fairs are mostly located in communities with historic or current agricultural activity, and feature local farmers exhibiting produce in addition to more high-profile commercial activities such as carnival rides, concerts and food.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] "Alaska Grown" is used as an agricultural slogan.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska has an abundance of seafood, with the primary fisheries in the Bering Sea and the North Pacific.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Seafood is one of the few food items that is often cheaper within the state than outside it.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Many Alaskans take advantage of salmon seasons to harvest portions of their household diet while fishing for subsistence, as well as sport.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] This includes fish taken by hook, net or wheel.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Hunting for subsistence, primarily caribou, moose, and Dall sheep is still common in the state, particularly in remote Bush communities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] An example of a traditional native food is Akutaq, the Eskimo ice cream, which can consist of reindeer fat, seal oil, dried fish meat and local berries.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's reindeer herding is concentrated on Seward Peninsula, where wild caribou can be prevented from mingling and migrating with the domesticated reindeer.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Most food in Alaska is transported into the state from "Outside" (the other 49 U.S. states), and shipping costs make food in the cities relatively expensive.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In rural areas, subsistence hunting and gathering is an essential activity because imported food is prohibitively expensive.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Although most small towns and villages in Alaska lie along the coastline, the cost of importing food to remote villages can be high because of the terrain and difficult road conditions, which change dramatically due to varying climate and precipitation changes.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Transport costs can reach 50¢ per pound ($1.10/kg) or higher in some remote areas during times of inclement weather or rough terrain conditions, if these locations can be reached at all.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The cost of delivering a gallon (3.8 L) of milk is about $3.50 in many villages where per capita income can be $20,000 or less.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Fuel cost per gallon is routinely twenty to thirty cents higher than the contiguous United States average, with only Hawaii having higher prices.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Some of Alaska's popular annual events are the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, World Ice Art Championships in Fairbanks, the Blueberry Festival and Alaska Hummingbird Festival in Ketchikan, the Sitka Whale Fest, and the Stikine River Garnet Fest in Wrangell.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Stikine River attracts the largest springtime concentration of American bald eagles in the world.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Heritage Center celebrates the rich heritage of Alaska's 11 cultural groups.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Their purpose is to encourage cross-cultural exchanges among all people and enhance self-esteem among Native people.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Native Arts Foundation promotes and markets Native art from all regions and cultures in the State, using the internet.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Influences on music in Alaska include the traditional music of Alaska Natives as well as folk music brought by later immigrants from Russia and Europe.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Prominent musicians from Alaska include singer Jewel, traditional Aleut flautist Mary Youngblood, folk singer-songwriter Libby Roderick, Christian music singer-songwriter Lincoln Brewster, metal/post hardcore band 36 Crazyfists and the groups Pamyua and Portugal.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] There are many established music festivals in Alaska, including the Alaska Folk Festival, the Fairbanks Summer Arts Festival, the Anchorage Folk Festival, the Athabascan Old-Time Fiddling Festival, the Sitka Jazz Festival, the Sitka Summer Music Festival, and the Anchorage Chamber Music Festival.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The most prominent orchestra in Alaska is the Anchorage Symphony Orchestra, though the Fairbanks Symphony Orchestra and Juneau Symphony are also notable.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Anchorage Opera is currently the state's only professional opera company, though there are several volunteer and semi-professional organizations in the state as well.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The official state song of Alaska is "Alaska's Flag", which was adopted in 1955; it celebrates the flag of Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The 1983 Disney movie *Never Cry Wolf* was at least partially shot in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The 1991 film *White Fang*, based on Jack London's 1906 novel and starring Ethan Hawke, was filmed in and around Haines.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Steven Seagal's 1994 *On Deadly Ground*, starring Michael Caine, was filmed in part at the Worthington Glacier near Valdez.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Many reality television shows are filmed in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2011, the *Anchorage Daily News* found ten set in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The following is a list of sporting venues, events, and teams based in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Troopers are Alaska's statewide police force.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] They have a long and storied history, but were not an official organization until 1941.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Before the force was officially organized, law enforcement in Alaska was handled by various federal agencies.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Larger towns usually have their own local police and some villages rely on "Public Safety Officers" who have police training but do not carry firearms.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In much of the state, the troopers serve as the only police force available.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In addition to enforcing traffic and criminal law, wildlife Troopers enforce hunting and fishing regulations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Due to the varied terrain and wide scope of the Troopers' duties, they employ a wide variety of land, air, and water patrol vehicles.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Many rural communities in Alaska are considered "dry", having outlawed the importation of alcoholic beverages.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Suicide rates for rural residents are higher than urban rates.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Domestic abuse and other violent crimes are at high levels in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] This is in part linked to alcohol abuse.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska has the highest rate of sexual assault in the nation, especially in rural areas.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The average age of sexually assaulted victims is 16 years old.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In four out of five cases, the suspects were relatives, friends, or acquaintances.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] As of 2022, CVS Health and Premera account for 47% and 46% of private health insurance, respectively.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Premera and Moda Health offer insurance on the federally-run Affordable Care Exchange.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Providence Alaska Medical Center in Anchorage is the largest hospital in the state as of 2021; Anchorage also hosts Alaska Regional Hospital and Alaska Native Medical Center.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's other major cities such as Fairbanks and Juneau also have local hospitals.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In Southeast Alaska, Southeast Alaska Regional Health Consortium, runs healthcare facilities across 27 communities as of 2022, including hospitals in Sitka and Wrangell; although it originally served Native Americans only, it has expanded access and combined with other local facilities over time.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Education and Early Development administers many school districts in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In addition, the state operates a boarding school, Mt.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Edgecumbe High School in Sitka, and provides partial funding for other boarding schools, including Nenana Student Living Center in Nenana and The Galena Interior Learning Academy in Galena.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] There are more than a dozen colleges and universities in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Accredited universities in Alaska include the University of Alaska Anchorage, University of Alaska Fairbanks, University of Alaska Southeast, and Alaska Pacific University.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska is the only state that has no collegiate athletic programs that are members of NCAA Division I, although both Alaska-Fairbanks and Alaska-Anchorage maintain single sport membership in Division I for men's ice hockey.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development operates AVTEC, Alaska's Institute of Technology.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Campuses in Seward and Anchorage offer one-week to 11-month training programs in areas as diverse as Information Technology, Welding, Nursing, and Mechanics.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska has had a problem with a "brain drain".
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Many of its young people, including most of the highest academic achievers, leave the state after high school graduation and do not return.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] As of 2013 Alaska did not have a law school or medical school.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The University of Alaska has attempted to combat this by offering partial four-year scholarships to the top 10% of Alaska high school graduates, via the Alaska Scholars Program.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Beginning in 1998, schools in rural Alaska must have at least ten students to retain funding from the state, and campuses not meeting the number close.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] This was due to the loss in oil revenues that previously propped up smaller rural schools.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2015, there was a proposal to raise that minimum to 25, but legislators in the state largely did not agree.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska has few road connections compared to the rest of the U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The state's road system, covering a relatively small area of the state, linking the central population centers and the Alaska Highway, the principal route out of the state through Canada.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The state capital, Juneau, is not accessible by road, with access only by ferry or flight; this has spurred debate over decades about moving the capital to a city on the road system, or building a road connection from Haines.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The western part of Alaska has no road system connecting the communities with the rest of Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Interstate Highways in Alaska consists of a total of 1,082 miles (1,741 km).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] These are mostly not built to Interstate Highway standards and their status as such is largely notional.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] A unique feature of the Alaska Highway system is the Anton Anderson Memorial Tunnel, an active Alaska Railroad tunnel that provides a paved roadway link with the isolated community of Whittier on Prince William Sound to the Seward Highway about 50 miles (80 km) southeast of Anchorage at Portage.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] At 2.5 miles (4.0 km), the tunnel was the longest road tunnel in North America until 2007.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The tunnel is the longest combination road and rail tunnel in North America.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Southwest Alaska is largely coastal, sparsely populated, and unconnected to the road system.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Access to most communities in Southwest Alaska is primarily by air taxi, although larger towns like Kodiak, Bethel, King Salmon, Dillingham, and Dutch Harbor are accessible by scheduled air service.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Some coastal communities can be reached via the Alaska Marine Highway ferry.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Built around 1915, the Alaska Railroad (ARR) played a key role in the development of Alaska through the 20th century.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] It links shipping lanes on the North Pacific with Interior Alaska with tracks that run from Seward by way of South Central Alaska, passing through Anchorage, Eklutna, Wasilla, Talkeetna, Denali, and Fairbanks, with spurs to Whittier, Palmer and North Pole.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The cities, towns, villages, and region served by ARR tracks are known statewide as "The Railbelt".
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In recent years, the ever-improving paved highway system began to eclipse the railroad's importance in Alaska's economy.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The railroad played a vital role in Alaska's development, moving freight into Alaska while transporting natural resources southward, such as coal from the Usibelli coal mine near Healy to Seward and gravel from the Matanuska Valley to Anchorage.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] It is well known for its summertime tour passenger service.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Railroad was one of the last railroads in North America to use cabooses in regular service and still uses them on some gravel trains.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] It continues to offer one of the last flag stop routes in the country.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] A stretch of about 60 miles (100 km) of track along an area north of Talkeetna remains inaccessible by road; the railroad provides the only transportation to rural homes and cabins in the area.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Until construction of the Parks Highway in the 1970s, the railroad provided the only land access to most of the region along its entire route.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In northern Southeast Alaska, the White Pass and Yukon Route also partly runs through the state from Skagway northwards into Canada (British Columbia and Yukon Territory), crossing the border at White Pass Summit.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] This line is now mainly used by tourists, often arriving by cruise liner at Skagway.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] It was featured in the 1983 BBC television series *Great Little Railways*.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] These two railroads are connected neither to each other nor any other railroad.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The nearest link to the North American railway network is the northwest terminus of the Canadian National Railway at Prince Rupert, British Columbia, several hundred miles to the southeast.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Congress authorized $6 million to study the feasibility of a rail link between Alaska, Canada, and the lower 48.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] As of 2021 the Alaska-Alberta Railway Development Corporation is in receivership.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Some private companies provides car float service between Whittier and Seattle.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Many cities, towns, and villages in Alaska don't have road or highway access.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The only modes of access involve travel by air, river, or the sea.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's well-developed state-owned ferry system, known as the Alaska Marine Highway, serves the cities of southeast, the Gulf Coast and the Alaska Peninsula.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The ferries transport vehicles and passengers.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The system also operates a ferry service from Bellingham, Washington and Prince Rupert, British Columbia, in Canada through the Inside Passage to Skagway.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Inter-Island Ferry Authority also serves as an important marine link for many communities in the Prince of Wales Island region of Southeast and works in concert with the Alaska Marine Highway.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In recent years, cruise lines have created a summertime tourism market, mainly connecting the Pacific Northwest to Southeast Alaska and, to a lesser degree, towns along Alaska's gulf coast.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The population of Ketchikan for example fluctuates dramatically on many days—up to four large cruise ships can dock there at the same time.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Cities not served by road, sea, or river can be reached only by air, foot, dogsled, or snowmachine, accounting for Alaska's extremely well developed bush air services—an Alaskan novelty.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Anchorage, and to a lesser extent Fairbanks, is served by many major airlines.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Because of limited highway access, air travel remains the most efficient form of transportation in and out of the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Anchorage recently completed extensive remodeling and construction at Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport to help accommodate the upsurge in tourism.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2012–2013, Alaska received almost two million visitors.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Making regular flights to most villages and towns within the state commercially viable is difficult, so they are heavily subsidized by the federal government through the Essential Air Service program.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The bulk of remaining commercial flight offerings come from small regional commuter airlines such as Ravn Alaska, PenAir, and Frontier Flying Service.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The smallest towns and villages must rely on scheduled or chartered bush flying services using general aviation aircraft such as the Cessna Caravan, the most popular aircraft in use in the state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Much of this service can be attributed to the Alaska bypass mail program which subsidizes bulk mail delivery to Alaskan rural communities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The program requires 70% of that subsidy to go to carriers who offer passenger service to the communities.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Many communities have small air taxi services.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] These operations originated from the demand for customized transport to remote areas.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Perhaps the most quintessentially Alaskan plane is the bush seaplane.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The world's busiest seaplane base is Lake Hood, located next to Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport, where flights bound for remote villages without an airstrip carry passengers, cargo, and many items from stores and warehouse clubs.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2006, Alaska had the highest number of pilots per capita of any U.S. state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In Alaska there are 8,795 active pilot certificates as of 2020.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Another Alaskan transportation method is the dogsled.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In modern times, that is, any time after the mid- to late‑1920s, dog mushing is more of a sport than a true means of transportation.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Races are held around the state, but the best known is the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, a 1,150-mile (1,850 km) trail from Anchorage to Nome, although the distance varies from year to year, the official distance is set at 1,049 miles or 1,688 km.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The race commemorates the famous 1925 serum run to Nome in which mushers and dogs like Togo and Balto took much-needed medicine to the diphtheria-stricken community of Nome when all other means of transportation had failed.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Mushers from all over the world come to Anchorage each March to compete for cash, prizes, and prestige.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The "Serum Run" is another sled dog race that more accurately follows the route of the famous 1925 relay, leaving from the community of Nenana, southwest of Fairbanks, to Nome.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In areas not served by road or rail, primary transportation in summer is by fourwheeler and in winter by snowmachine.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's internet and other data transport systems are provided largely through the two major telecommunications companies: GCI and Alaska Communications.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] GCI owns and operates what it calls the Alaska United Fiber Optic system.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] As of late 2011, Alaska Communications had two fiber optic paths to the lower 48 and two more across Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In January 2011, it was reported that a $1 billion project to connect Asia and rural Alaska was being planned, aided in part by $350 million in stimulus from the federal government.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The state of Alaska employs approximately 16,000 people statewide.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska State Legislature consists of a 40-member House of Representatives and a 20-member Senate.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Senators serve four-year terms and House members two.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The governor of Alaska serves four-year terms.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The lieutenant governor runs separately from the governor in the primaries, but during the general election, the nominee for governor and nominee for lieutenant governor run together on the same ticket.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's court system has four levels: the Alaska Supreme Court, the Alaska Court of Appeals, the Superior Court and the district courts.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The superior and district courts are trial courts.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Superior courts are courts of general jurisdiction, while district courts hear only certain types of cases, including misdemeanor criminal cases and civil cases valued up to $100,000.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court and the Court of Appeals are appellate courts.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Court of Appeals is required to hear appeals from certain lower-court decisions, including those regarding criminal prosecutions, juvenile delinquency, and habeas corpus.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Supreme Court hears civil appeals and may in its discretion hear criminal appeals.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Although in its early years of statehood Alaska was a Democratic state, since the early 1970s it has been characterized as Republican-leaning.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Local political communities have often worked on issues related to land use development, fishing, tourism, and individual rights.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska Natives, while organized in and around their communities, have been active within the Native corporations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] These have been given ownership over large tracts of land, which require stewardship.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska was formerly the only state in which possession of one ounce or less of marijuana in one's home was completely legal under state law, though the federal law remains in force.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The state has an independence movement favoring a vote on secession from the United States, with the Alaskan Independence Party.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Six Republicans and four Democrats have served as governor of Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Republican governor Wally Hickel was elected to the office for a second term in 1990 after leaving the Republican party and briefly joining the Alaskan Independence Party ticket just long enough to be reelected.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] He rejoined the Republican party in 1994.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska's voter initiative making marijuana legal took effect in February 2015, placing Alaska alongside Colorado and Washington, as well as Washington D.C., as the first three U.S. states where recreational marijuana is legal.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The law means people over 21 can consume small amounts of cannabis.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The first legal marijuana store opened in Valdez in October 2016.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] To finance state government operations, Alaska depends primarily on petroleum revenues and federal subsidies.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] This allows it to have the lowest individual tax burden in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] It is one of five states with no sales tax, one of seven states with no individual income tax, and—along with New Hampshire—one of two that has neither.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Department of Revenue Tax Division reports regularly on the state's revenue sources.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The department issues an annual summary of its operations, including new state laws that directly affect the tax division.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2014, the Tax Foundation ranked Alaska as having the fourth most "business friendly" tax policy, behind only Wyoming, South Dakota, and Nevada.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] 89 municipalities collect a local sales tax, from 1.0 to 7.5%, typically 3–5%.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Other local taxes levied include raw fish taxes, hotel, motel, and bed-and-breakfast 'bed' taxes, severance taxes, liquor and tobacco taxes, gaming (pull tabs) taxes, tire taxes and fuel transfer taxes.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] A part of the revenue collected from certain state taxes and license fees, such as petroleum, aviation motor fuel, telephone cooperative, is shared with municipalities in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The fall in oil prices after the fracking boom in the early 2010s has decimated Alaska's state treasury, which has historically received about 85 percent of its revenue from taxes and fees imposed on oil and gas companies.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The state government has had to drastically reduce its budget, and has brought its budget shortfall from over $2 billion in 2016 to under $500 million by 2018.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2020, Alaska's state government budget was $4.8 billion, while projected government revenues were only $4.5 billion.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska regularly supports Republicans in presidential elections and has done so since statehood.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Republicans have won the state's electoral college votes in all but one election that it has participated in (1964).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] No state has voted for a Democratic presidential candidate fewer times.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska was carried by Democratic nominee Lyndon B.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Johnson during his landslide election in 1964, while the 1960 and 1968 elections were close.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Since 1972, Republicans have carried the state by large margins.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2008, Republican John McCain defeated Democrat Barack Obama in Alaska, 59.49% to 37.83%.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] McCain's running mate was Sarah Palin, the state's governor and the first Alaskan on a major party ticket.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Obama lost Alaska again in 2012, but he captured 40% of the state's vote in that election, making him the first Democrat to do so since 1968.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In 2020, Joe Biden received 42.77% of the vote for president, marking the high point for a Democratic presidential candidate since Johnson's 1964 victory.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Alaska Bush, central Juneau, midtown and downtown Anchorage, and the areas surrounding the University of Alaska Fairbanks campus and Ester have been strongholds of the Democratic Party.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The Matanuska-Susitna Borough, the Kenai Peninsula, the majority of Fairbanks (including North Pole and the military base), and South Anchorage typically have the strongest Republican showing.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Alaska has a history of primary defeats for incumbent U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Senators, including Ernest Gruening, Mike Gravel, and Lisa Murkowski.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] However, Murkowski won re-election with a write-in campaign.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Despite this, Alaska has also seen long-serving members of Congress, such as Ted Stevens, who served as a U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Senator for 40 years, and Don Young, who held Alaska's sole U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] House seat for 49 years, from 1973 to 2022.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] In the 2020 election cycle, Alaskan voters approved Ballot Measure 2.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The measure passed by a margin of 1.1%, or about 4,000 votes.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The measure requires campaigns to disclose the original source and any intermediaries for campaign contributions over $2,000.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The measure also establishes non-partisan primaries, sometimes called jungle primaries, for statewide elections (like in Washington state and California) and ranked-choice voting, like in Maine.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] Measure 2 makes Alaska the third state with nonpartisan primaries for all statewide races, the second state with ranked choice voting, and the only state with both.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] The 2022 special election to fill Alaska's only U.S.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] House seat, left vacant by the death of Don Young, was won by Mary Peltola.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] She became the first Democrat to win the House seat since 1972 and the first Alaskan Native elected to the United States Congress in history.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-p02] After winning a full term in the 2022 general election, Peltola lost reelection in 2024 to Republican Nick Begich III.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The **Alaska Peninsula** (also called the **Aleut Peninsula** or the **Aleutian Peninsula**, Aleut: *Alaxsxix̂*; Sugpiaq: *Aluuwiq*, *Al'uwiq*) is a peninsula extending about 497 mi (800 km) to the southwest from the mainland of Alaska and ending in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The peninsula separates the Pacific Ocean from Bristol Bay, an arm of the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] In literature (especially Russian), the term *Alaska Peninsula* was used to denote the entire north-western protrusion of the North American continent, or all of what is now the state of Alaska, exclusive of its panhandle and islands.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The Lake and Peninsula borough, the Alaskan equivalent of a county, is named after the peninsula.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The Alaska/Aleutian Peninsula is also grouped into Southwest Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The other large peninsulas in Alaska include the Kenai Peninsula and the Seward Peninsula.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The base of the Alaska Peninsula extends outward from the end of the Alaska Range.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The Aleutian Range is a very active volcanic mountain range which runs along the entire length of the peninsula.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Within it lie Wildlife Refuges, including the Katmai National Park and Preserve, the Aniakchak National Monument and Preserve and the Becharof National Wildlife Refuge, the Alaska Peninsula National Wildlife Refuge, and the Izembek National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The most active volcano along the volcanic mountain range is Pavlof Volcano which is more than 8,251 feet (2,515 meters)(see also: Aleutian Arc).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The northern and southern shores are likewise quite different.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The northern Bristol Bay coastal side is generally turbid and muddy, experiences tidal extremes, and is relatively shallow; the Pacific side, which is also known as the "ring of fire", has relatively small tidal activity and the water is deep and clear.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The peninsula is organized as a part of four adjacent boroughs; the Aleutians East Borough, Bristol Bay Borough, Kodiak Island Borough, and Lake and Peninsula Borough.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The Lake and Peninsula Borough includes most of the peninsula's territory.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Average annual precipitation ranges from 24–65 in (610–1,650 mm).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Coastal areas are subject to intense storms, wind, and rain.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Winter temperatures average between 12 and 34 °F (−11 and 1 °C), and in summer between 43 and 59 °F (6 and 15 °C).
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Frosts can occur any day of the year at higher elevations.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The climate can be compared to that of parts of Scotland, the Aleutian Islands, Iceland, and Tierra del Fuego.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The Alaska Peninsula is home to some of the largest populations of native and undisturbed wildlife in the United States.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Besides the famous McNeil River and Katmai Alaskan brown bear populations, large herds of caribou, moose, wolves, waterfowl, and willow ptarmigan inhabit the area.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The bears of the peninsula and Bristol Bay are so numerous because they feed on the world's largest sockeye salmon (*Oncorhynchus nerka*) runs, which occur here in large part because the many large lakes of the peninsula are an important element in their lifecycle.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] These salmon, after returning from their brief time at sea, swim into the lakes and their contributing streams to spawn.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Their offspring, or *fry*, overwinter in the deep and food-abundant depths of these lakes until their migration to the sea in one or two years.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Exceptionally large seabird colonies exist along the coast.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Additionally, there are large populations of sea mammals in the North Pacific Ocean between the Alaska Peninsula and Kamchatka.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] This includes harbor seals, ringed seals, northern fur seals, whales, porpoises, sea otters and sea lions.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] The rugged southern half of the peninsula, and also the Kodiak Archipelago which lie off the south coast of the peninsula and are home to even more bears, constitute the Alaska Peninsula montane taiga ecoregion and contain a number of protected areas such as Katmai National Park.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Vegetation on the peninsula consists mostly of shrub-lands, grassy meadows, or wet tundra.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Besides the communities on the coast (*see: Bristol Bay*), the Alaska Peninsula also is home to several well-known villages: Cold Bay, King Cove, Perryville, Chignik, Chignik Lake, Chignik Lagoon, and Port Moller.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-peninsula] Each is primarily inhabited by Alaska Natives and each, likewise, is mostly dependent on the fishing industry for sustenance.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Since Alaska became a U.S. state in 1959, it has sent congressional delegations to the United States Senate and United States House of Representatives.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Each state elects two senators to serve for six years, and member(s) of the House to two-year terms.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Before becoming a state, the Territory of Alaska elected a non-voting delegate at-large to Congress from 1906 to 1959.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] These are tables of congressional delegations from Alaska to the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Alaska's current congressional delegation in the 119th Congress consists of its two senators, who are both Republicans and its sole representative, who is a Republican.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] The current dean of the Alaska delegation is Senator Lisa Murkowski having served in the Senate since 2002.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Lisa Murkowski is the first elected senator born in Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Each state elects two senators by statewide popular vote every six years.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] The terms of the two senators are staggered so that they are not elected in the same year, meaning that each seat also has a class determining the years in which the seat will be up for election.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Alaska's senators are elected in classes 2 and 3.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] There have been eight senators from Alaska, of whom four have been Democrats and four have been Republicans.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] William Egan and Ernest Gruening were elected to the Senate on October 6, 1956 for the 84th Congress but did not take the oath of office and were not accorded senatorial privileges, since Alaska was not yet a state.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Alaska's current senators, both Republicans, are Dan Sullivan, in office since 2015, and Lisa Murkowski, in office since 2002.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Starting on August 14, 1906, Alaska sent a non-voting delegate to the House.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] From May 17, 1884 to August 24, 1912, Alaska was designated as the District of Alaska.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] From then to January 3, 1959, it was the Alaska Territory.
[src:alaska-peninsula/alaska-s-congressional-delegations] Since statehood on January 3, 1959, Alaska has had one seat in the House.
